What is Software Testing?

Software Testing is the process of evaluating a system or application to find defects and ensure it works as expected.

Objectives:
Find bugs/errors
Ensure requirements are met
Improve quality
Verify performance & security
🔸 Types of Software Testing
 1. Functional Testing

Tests what the system does.

Unit Testing → Individual components
Integration Testing → Combined modules
System Testing → Entire system
Acceptance Testing → User validation

 Example: Checking login functionality works correctly.

 2. Non-Functional Testing

Tests how the system performs.

Performance Testing (speed, load)
Security Testing (data protection)
Usability Testing (user experience)
Compatibility Testing (browser, device)

 Example: Checking website load under heavy traffic.

3. Manual Testing
Done by humans without tools
Exploratory and user-based testing
4. Automation Testing
Uses tools/scripts (e.g., Selenium)
Faster and repeatable
 5. Other Testing Types
Regression Testing → After changes
Smoke Testing → Basic checks
Sanity Testing → Quick validation
Beta Testing → Real users
🔹 2. What is Software Quality Assurance (SQA)?

SQA is a process-oriented approach that ensures quality in every phase of development, not just testing.

 Testing = Finding bugs
SQA = Preventing bugs

🔸Key Activities in SQA
 1. Requirement Analysis
Ensure requirements are clear and testable
 2. Test Planning
Define strategy, tools, timeline
 3. Test Case Design
Write test cases and scenarios
4. Test Execution
Run test cases and log defects
 5. Defect Tracking
Track bugs using tools (e.g., JIRA)
 6. Test Reporting
Generate reports and metrics
🔹 3. Difference: Testing vs SQA
Aspect	Testing	SQA
Focus	Product	Process
Goal	Find defects	Prevent defects
Timing	After development	Throughout SDLC
Approach	Reactive	Proactive
